    "His most popular course at Harvard was \"The History of the Fine Arts as Connected with Literature.\"": [],
    "His collected Harvard lectures, published in 1891 as <em>History of Ancient Art</em>, belie the debt to Ruskin's Oxford lectures on beauty as a source for moral uprightness.": [],
    "Norton was the literary executor for Ruskin as well as Thomas Carlyle (1795-1881).": [],
    "As a man of letters, Norton maintained a correspondence with many of the later 19th-century authors, including Charles Dickens, Matthew Arnold, Charles Darwin, Robert Browning and Ralph Waldo Emerson.": [],
    "His cottage in Ashfield in the Massachusetts Berkshires as well as Shady Hill, his home in Cambridge (Massachusetts) were the meeting place for many intellectuals and discussions.": [
